,Recommended,266010,29016466,Posted: 4 January,all,Lu,"Nice game, nice achievements. Waiting for Lyne 2."
,Not Recommended,266010,32400028,Posted: 13 June,all,changarid,"Lyne is a puzzle game inspired by the Nine-dot problem. The game introduces multiple lines  with separate sets of target dots distinguished by different colors. As anothre addition, there are vertices at which the lines are allowed to cross. While the original puzzle is a nice demonstration of insight problem-solving and out-of-box thinking, solution of Lyne puzzles does not involve either of these. Rather the solution is achieved by an exhaustive and often random exploration of the tree of all possible states. The difficulty is increased by asking the player to solve puzzles with deeper and wider trees.The controls are lacking: It is possible to modify the line that has been drawn only at its end. If you want to modify a segment of line at where it started, you need to redraw the entire line. That's not a big deal with small puzzles but it can get annoying with more longer lines.The game is intended for screens with portrait rotation - i.e. screens with height>width. Such choice is awkward since most displays are intended for landscape viewing and, for instance, it's not feasable to physically rotate laptop screen or a projector display.  As a consequence some slim puzzles will occupy 1/8 of the width of your screen when viewed in landscape mode and it can get really tricky to accurately draw the desired line.It appears that the game partly gets its current overwhelming rating due to the attractivity of its achievements. Achievements aside, I don't think the game deserves such rating. I don't recommend it."
