76561198108154287,Recommended,266010,16418007,"Posted: 15 June, 2015",all,ᅚ,"It's a very simple puzzle game, with one concept: connect like-shaped/colored blocks. You click on the beginning block of a certain color, and drag a path to the finishing block. It's very basic and simple, but it gets more complex when more colors are added, as well as when conjunction blocks are added that can have multiple paths go through them. I only got a couple hours of fun out of it since it's incredibly redundant, but if you're bored or want to exercise your brain a little bit, LYNE isn't a bad place to start. It has a very simplistic and sleek design, which isn't hard on the eyes."
,Recommended,266010,18210666,"Posted: 26 September, 2015",all,JacquesLeSauve,"Now THIS is how you make a puzzle game! Both elegant in its simplicity and devious in its complexity, LYNE is a beautiful blend of pick-up-and-play accessibility and fair, reasonable challenge that pretty much never punishes and only rewards. I'm not sure of the exact terminology of every element of the game, so I'm just going to have to wing it and hope it all makes sense...The easiest way to probably explain it is to say it's a game of join the dots. There are three main coloured shapes, or nodes, scattered across a gridded board, green triangles, red squares and blue diamonds (at least by default, the colour palette can be unlocked and changed throughout the game), with a start and end point for each shape. The object being to drag a line that joins each point whilst also passing through all the faded out nodes of the same shape. So the green line can only pass through the faded green nodes, and so on. There are also neutral nodes that any line can pass through which act as intersections for the different coloured lines. With the exception of these neutral nodes, each node can only be passed through once, either vertically, horizontally or diagonally, and a line can never cross through another line. So, basically, connect each start and end point, and fill in the board along the way. As with most puzzle games, it can sound way more complicated in writing than it really is, but within thirty seconds of actual play you'll perfectly understand exactly how the whole thing works.The game's first triumph is in teaching itself to the player. With the way it introduces each element of play, the only actions you'll be able to perform are the ones it wants you to learn, further reinforced by brief phases of repetition and minor variation. It won't take long for the series of light bulbs to come on over your head with each new method of covering the board that you learn and you'll soon find yourself steamrolling your way through the opening few stages.There are 26 sets of puzzles corrosponding to each letter of the alphabet, with each set containing 25 individual puzzles for a total of 650... yeah, you read that right, 650 puzzles. On top of that there are also random daily sets, but unless I'm mistaken, they at least appeared to me to be a mix of various puzzles from the main sets. It's hard to say how long it takes to complete, given that each player will spend a vastly different amount of time depending on their personal skill level, but I reckon about 30 hours would be a reasonable guess, give or take a few hours.What I really love about this game is how success or failure rests solely in the hands of the player's own determination. With no time limit and no way to technically lose (you either finish a puzzle or you walk away from it), the game is a test of perseverance more than anything. There are a few tricks you can learn to criss-cross your way around a board, but really you'll have to poke and prod at everything and experiment with different routes before honing in on the solution. But rarely will the game leave you hanging, and it'll usually hint as to where you should at least start before working your way out, and from there on it's a gradual process of elimination. It also helps that many puzzles will have multiple methods to solve them, so there is some flexibility in play.Topping everything off is a slick, clean aesthetic that's minimalist but still appealing. I wasn't a massive fan of the audio as the pinging chimes gradually grated against me and I instead opted to play my own music in the background the entire time, but that's a very minor gripe given how it doesn't really serve any fuctional role in the game play and you can easily live without it. But what I was a massive fan off was the price which is the sweet little cherry on top that should be the final nudge to any fence-sitters still not entirely sure whether or not they should pick this up. Protip, you should."
,Recommended,266010,12180311,"Posted: 21 September, 2014",all,Nahuta,"I've said this multiple times in my walkthrough videos for this game, but I still can't say it enough.  This is one of the best executed indie puzzle games I've seen.  It's simple without being dumbed down, complex enough without being confusing, and provides enough challenge to keep from being repetitive without being overly frustrating.  I spent enough time in the game to get the full 999/999 but never felt like the game was a grind to do so.  Definitely worth it."
