76561197960531283,Recommended,266010,9568413,"Posted: 19 March, 2014",all,Powdertoast,"I certainly recommend this game to people who like casual abstract puzzle games. This isn't Rubik's Cube, but some of the levels can be downright diabolically devious to overcome. There's never a time limit, you can work on each level as long as you'd like. It's also one of those games that you can pick up, play five minutes, and put away. Unfortunately, it has a very strong ""Just one more level"" factor to counterbalance. The graphics are simple and elegant, very smooth, and very very effective at teaching the game to players without resorting to any language. Seriously, this game's look and feel teaches players how to play so effeciently that you find yourself automatically doing what it's asking without thinking about it. The learning curve isn't very steep, but the complexity mounts tremendously, moving from easy trial and error solutions to thought requirements then some trial and error. There's no scoring, just how many levels you've beaten. It's simple, beautiful, and a joy to work with. It's also available for Android, and I've already snapped it up for my phone and tablet. My five-year-old picked it up pretty quickly, too. Try it out!"
