,Recommended,266010,10732484,"Posted: 23 June, 2014",all,Gett Numbers,"LYNE is something I haven't found in a while; a simple puzzle game with a casual element to it. I've always loved casual puzzle games but I've never been able to find many, especially in recent times. I love the concept for being such a simple yet malleable one. All you do is connect lines. That's it, but, adding more simple ideas, such as different colors and looping lines through themselves, gives this game a great variety and suprising difficulty.And it's not short either. There's 26 sets with 25 puzzles for each one and a steady increase in difficulty, introducing harder mechanics throughout every 1 or 2 sets. But what happens when you get through all of those? Where do I go now? Well, there's a wonderful daily system in place that randomly generates 1-3 sets, each with a varying degree of difficulty. Each day, you can come back and play a new daily set of sets, giving this simple game a huge replayability.However, there are some minor, minor problems. One of which is the difficulty spikes. One puzzle in a set usually has me there for at least 5 minutes whereas the rest of them are around a minute or less. Now that's too bad, as getting stuck helps me get better at thinking in different ways; looking at things in a different perspective. Although, it is slightly annoying to be stuck on a puzzle for so long. Also, some people may complain about the ""lack of tutorial"" when introducing new things, but that's what makes this game unique and stylized. That's what makes it so rewarding to solve a puzzle that you've been on for 5 minutes or longer.But the best thing by far in the game is the atmosphere. The sounds and the ability to change palette really sold me on this game. I thoroughly enjoy just clicking on the shapes and listening to the sounds ping off, and then connecting makes shapes gives me a little reward. When you complete a puzzle, a simple ambient sound resonates through into the next level and the screen goes white, knowing that I solved the puzzle and that this is my reward. When I don't complete a puzzle, it tells me what things I need to connect and flashes at me in red to help me guide my way into solving the puzzle.All in all, this game is great at what it does and took a very simple concept and expanded it greatly. With it's wonderful sound and level design, it did great to suck me and it seems like a game I would play for years. Basically, purchase it now. It's cheap enough to not pick up. Buy it now!"
