,Recommended,266010,18345827,"Posted: 5 October, 2015",all,ErickaUnlimited,"OverviewLyne is a simple, yet intuitive indie puzzle game that revolves around creating ""pathways"" that link matching shapes together without crossing paths of other color variants. Honestly, that is the goal of every puzzle in the game, but what I enjoyed about Lyne was the variety in which you could complete such a simple task. The game takes you through the letters of the alphabet and, as you'd probably guess, the further along you go, the harder and more complex the puzzles become. You start out with two colors and a simple solution is often identified quickly, allowing you to seamlessly glide through the first set of puzzles. As you progress, the game adds sort of ""gateways"" in which a set number of lines, or lynes if you will, can pass through without conflicting with one another; think of it as a sort of intersection.As time progresses , the game adds more shapes to match and gateways to fill and it can become quite complicated, but never frustratingly so, in my opinion. What I enjoyed about the difficulty is it never really spiked; the game gradually increased the challenge as you progressed. I never felt annoyed or frustrated at puzzles I could not figure out and that is what I loved about Lyne.The game's simple, yet soothing atmosphere makes it a pleasure, even when you can't, for the life of it all, figure out the solution. Aside from all that, what I enjoy most about Lyne are the daily puzzles. These are randomly generated each day and vary in difficulty - from easy to extreme. This added feature gives the game replay-ability when you feel like sitting down and cracking out a few puzzles to unwind, or for a mental challenge. If you like puzzle games, I'd suggest Lyne.ProsChallenge - Lyne can be tough, but gentle. It never seems unfair just for the sake of challenging you.Replay-ability - With daily puzzles to try, even after you beat the game there is still always something to try.Visuals - Lyne is simple, yet nice to look at and to listen to. You may also unlock new color modes to select what works best for your eyesight and ascetic tastes.ConsCons - It is hard to say. I like to think every game can improve itself, but it's hard to find something in Lyne I didn't enjoy. I suppose it would be nice to have more puzzles each day if you complete the daily ones; perhaps an option to randomly generate some based on your desired difficulty setting.Overall, I enjoyed Lyne. I originally bought it for the achievements to use in my profile, but found I got a lot more for my money than just virtual achievements and I was very pleased. If you enjoy puzzle games and are looking for something new, I suggest checking Lyne out."
