,Recommended,266010,20239180,"Posted: 2 January, 2016",all,Mr.Husky #TeamBOOMBabY!,8/10
,Recommended,266010,20194768,"Posted: 1 January, 2016",all,Sellyme,"A surprisingly intuitive and easy to pick up puzzle game that introduces devilish complexity and a frankly staggeringly large number of levels (I'm an hour and a half in and I've only completed 75 out of 650 puzzles), coupled with the fact that at the time of review LYNE is on sale for just $0.89 means that it's an unbeatable buy. I have purchased several hundred games and LYNE is hands down bar none the best value for money.With a pleasant simplistic design that lets you get straight into the puzzle solving (which can take anywhere between half a second and half an hour per puzzle, depending on the difficulty), it's something that I wish we saw more of in modern video games. One of my largest gripes with puzzle games is when you're forced to sit through a several minute tutorial with mandatory wait times or - even worse! - having to watch the game do it for you at an antagonisingly slow pace. LYNE has no such tutorial. Instead, you learn the mechanics of the game through a series of a slowly ramping difficulty curve, and if the puzzles are too easy at the start (which they probably will be for anyone who's played similar games before), they take less than a second to complete and the next one loads rapidly, with no gimmicky ""congratulations!' screen or long celebration animations. You complete it, it slides off screen, and the next one slides in.All in all, LYNE is a solid 9.5/10 puzzle game. It's good for someone who just wants to fiddle around with a game for 10 minutes on a lunch break, or for someone who wants to spend hours if not days meticulously completing every single one of the 650 levels. I would highly recommend it, and at the current price, you'd be stupid not to buy it."
