,Recommended,266010,19303946,"Posted: 27 November, 2015",all,Apple of the Earth,"This game was really fun for the first few sets.  Then, it started to get a bit harder.  I wanted to write things out in my achievement showcase though, and I didn't want to just use Steam Achievement Manager or look up a guide.  That would more or less make the game a waste of money.After around six hours of this game over the course of two sessions, I started to get a severe case of the Tetris Effect.  Every time I closed my eyes, I would start connecting shapes together.  In the days that followed, my dreams consisted entirely of connecting shapes together and solving puzzles.I started to become frustrated with everyday life.  Why couldn't I connect shapes together in real life?  Why didn't connecting shapes together in my head solve my real world problems?That was a month and a half ago.  I have since picked the game up again, but I'm using a guide this time.  It's a compromise between having no fun and the shape-infested hell I was living in when I first started playing.  There are also randomly generated puzzles that are just as good as the normal ones, so if I start seeing shapes again, I can always just cheat all of the achievements and play the random levels afterward.Let it be known that I beat sets A-F and got partway through G before losing my mind.  I urge that if you want to play this game legitimately...at least pace yourself.  Otherwise, you could end up like me.Edit:  Today, scared of returning to shape-infested hell, I cheated the achievements."
,Not Recommended,266010,21139212,"Posted: 11 February, 2016",all,Trackpad Batman,"(Let me preface this by saying that I've completed two full letter sets and half of a third one, plus several daily sets.)I'm a big fan of minimalist/indie puzzle games, but this one leaves me cold. I've not invested the time that other reviewers have, but I can imagine from what I've seen that the mechanics of this game don't get any more complex as you progress. Each level set does become more difficult between its beginning and its end, but because there are so many level sets, it feels like playing the same game over and over again.There is no ambient soundtrack, which is for me an essential part of a minimalist puzzle game (although on the flip side, you can listen to your own music over it instead).There is no real logic to be applied to the solution process -- yes, there is a little bit of reasoning involved (this node has this number of empty slots, so this many paths will go through it; that color tile can only be accessed that way), but nothing engaging or stimulating. Any given puzzle often has multiple solutions, which is . . . nice, I guess, and uninteresting.There is, basically, nothing to DO. And with 26 sets of 25 levels each, plus new daily sets, there's a whole lot of nothing to do. I take another crack at this game every other evening to see if I just wasn't in the right frame of mind last time I played it, and every time I close it after a level or two, more bored than when I started. If it's on sale for less than $1, sure, buy it, get some achievements to make a funny message in your showcase. But if you're looking for a puzzle game that makes you really feel the blood flowing in your brain, play Hexcells.Really, play Hexcells anyway. It's a fantastic game."
