76561198081554978,Recommended,266010,13338237,"Posted: 12 December, 2014",all,The Government,"★★★⋆☆ (3.5/5 - Decent)(WARNING: This review contains mild spoilers)LYNE is one of those clever minimalistic games that focuses on providing simple but entertaining casual gameplay. Your aim in LYNE is to connect nodes of the same shape and colour in order to create one single line between them. Lines can travel between nodes and shapes in eight possible directions. Although this may seem like a simple procedure, there are certain elements in the game that can provide challenging and thought-provoking problems for the player.LYNE only requires the mouse to fully utilise the game, this along with simple gameplay makes LYNE very easy to pick up and play. You create lines by dragging between two nodes, to delete a node you simply reverse the process and drag back to the previous node. Occasionally clicking in the wrong location can also remove linked lines but this is rarely a problem and most players will only have this happen to them a couple of times so long as they're careful. The gameplay is smooth and menu and level transitions are practically flawless.When you begin the game you have access to a simple yet informative tutorial and getting your bearings on the game and understanding it is painless, within minutes you'll be clearing LYNE boards like there is no tomorrow.The graphics and effects in LYNE are minimal (hence the reason the game is classified as a minimalist game) but the effects and use of colours is relaxing and a high level of detail is definitely still present. Palettes help to excel the game and provide interesting colour and pattern combinations. The graphics all appear to be vector images and this makes the game clean and enhances its sense of tranquility further.The music of LYNE is probably the most important and most effective part of the game. The game prides itself as being a  ""relaxing puzzle game"". The music and sound effects is what makes this claim so abundantly true. The music itself is a relaxing blend of trance and drone-style ambience. Every time you join a line between nodes a soft calming note plays. Although simple, the gentle qualities of the notes and sounds used within the game easily ties it together as a whole.I would consider only playing this game in short periods to recieve the full effect of the game, playing it in long sessions can destroy the game for some people who see it as repetitive and boring. The game is fairly repetitive with each level set getting gradually more and more difficult, but if you play it in short bursts you should still find it fresh and enjoyable.This brings me to my next comment - replay value. The game as many have said can get boring after a while, but daily random levels of differing difficulty can help to provide more entertainment between the regular level sets. Also, as you complete level sets, both daily sets and the regular ones, you will recieve strange codebits known as ""Cipher"" which help you to unlock new colour palettes and other interesting content.The difficulty is almost spot on and rarely will you get stumped on levels that cannot be solved with 10 - 15 minutes. The amount of Cipher you earn in any given set correlates to the difficulty of the puzzle (e.g. 1 = easy set, 5 = very challenging etc.).Overall I would highly recommend LYNE to anyone who likes puzzle games or any casual gamers that are looking for a relaxing and fun game to ease their mind after a troubling day. Basically anyone can pick this game up and I encourage those interested to do so, I almost guarantee you will not be disappointed!Rating:Story = N / AGameplay & Controls = 4/5Graphics = 3.5/5Audio = 4/5Replay Value = 3/5Difficulty = 3.5/5"
