,Recommended,266010,26900032,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,D3C,"Bottom line (ahem),LYNEis a rare masterpiece of a game: simple, complex, complete and satisfying. If you are a fan of logic/puzzle games, I’d recommend not missing this gem.1) Minutes to learn, long time to master: LYNE’s gameplay is incredibly simple. You connect a beginning shape to an ending shape by drawing a line through similar shapes. That’s it—that’s the entire game. And yet, once puzzles start increasing in size and complexity, there’s a lot of challenge and a lot of satisfaction to be had from meeting the challenge.2) Colour and atmosphere: Progressing through level sets allows you to unlock different colour schemes, giving you 12 different palettes to chose from. The soundtrack is player generated: each move made in the puzzle sounds a harmonic chime, while finishing a puzzle rewards you with a sustained note that blends beautifully with the sounds of the next puzzle.3) It never ends: With 26 level sets containing 25 puzzles each, there are 650 levels for your enjoyment/frustration. Plus there’s an infinite set of random puzzles generated daily, moving up in complexity as the week progresses, to let you get a daily fix of twisted brain (if you’re into that sort of thing).4) Bletchley Park 2: Buried in the game is a hidden cipher (for the not-so-amateur codebreaker) which reveals parts of itself as you play, and spells out a personal message from the developer. Whether you want to try to crack it yourself, or just read through the Steam discussion thread and marvel at the dedication and cleverness of the community that solved it, it’s a neat touch that makes a great game just a little bit more personal."
